                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t16810413a-1-off2 t16810413a-1-crimeloc5"></join>; The Circumstances of the Robbery were, That Mead coming from Greenwich met two men near the Half way house; who bid him Stand and Deliver, or they would Pistol him; at which being much surprised, he endeavoured to escape them by setting Spurs to his Mare, but in vain, for they being well mounted, pursued and fired a Pistol at him, the which although it missed him, frighted him so as to oblige him to yield to their Mercy, who after they had taken from him about 7 shillings, a Pocket book, some pieces of Ribbon, and other things of little value, they took his Mare, the which upon search was found in an Inn at Westminster, where the Prisoner had ordered her standing, desiring that she might be kept private, and that if any Hue and Cry came; to give him notice of it, for that he had lately wounded a man that wounded him about 2 years since: The Prisoner Pleaded he had<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="16810413a002"></xptr>nothing to do with the Mare, but that a Boy brought her thither; but upon the Inn-keepers proving the contrary, and himself having confessed the Robbery, he was found <rs id="t16810413a-1-verdict6" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t16810413a-1-verdict6" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               Guilty
            </rs> of Stealing the Mare, Saddle, Bridle and Whip, the last being found in his Lodging Chamber, but as to the Robbery, in taking other things upon the High-way, that being done in another County, he could not be Tryed in Middlesex for the same.</p>
